initial_story: bias triangles represent features in stability diagrams of quantum dot (qd)devices, whose occurrence and property analysis are crucial indicators for spinphysics. nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and availability ofdata as well as the subtlety of physical phenomena of interest have hindered anautomatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) onhuman labelling and verification. we introduce a feature extraction frameworkfor bias triangles, built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer visionmethods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification ofphysical properties of the former. thereby, the need for human input or largetraining datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is circumvented,while additionally enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and featurelabeling. in particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (psb)detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any trainingdata as a direct result of this approach.
stories: Triangular biases are critical elements in stability diagrams of quantum dot devices, serving as important indicators for spin physics. However, challenges related to data quality and availability, along with the complexity of the physical phenomena involved, have impeded the development of an automated analysis framework, often still relying partially on human labeling and verification. We present a new framework for extracting features from bias triangles using unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision methods, which allows for the direct identification and measurement of their physical properties. This eliminates the need for human input or large training sets required for supervised learning, while also enabling automated labeling of shapes and features at the pixel level. Specifically, we show that pauli spin blockade detection can be effectively and efficiently carried out without any training data using this approach.

However, challenges related to data quality and availability, as well as the complexity of the physical phenomena involved, have hindered the development of an automated analysis framework, often still depending on human labeling and verification. We introduce a new framework for extracting features from bias triangles using unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision methods, enabling the direct identification and measurement of their physical properties. This eliminates the need for human input or large training sets required for supervised learning, while also allowing for automated labeling of shapes and features at the pixel level. In particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade detection can be effectively and efficiently performed without any training data using this approach.
